ers, which isn't ideal. I’m thinking about using NativeJavaObject with the constructor, including includeProtected as true since the isAdapter parameter is also true. But does that mean I need to import NativeJavaObject? I wonder if Context.javaToJS takes care of the includeProtected part or not. I’ll need to clarify this!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_PXqVgCnmrmJf80EvNnpPT4on|fc_070b330990e081ed0169f4e5f83be88197a512620809f778e2", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.sourceforge.htmlunit/htmlunit-core-js/2.70.0/src/test/java/net_sourceforge_htmlunit/htmlunit_core_js/JavaMembersTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.security.Permission;\n\nimport net.sourceforge.htmlunit.corejs.javascript.Context;", "newText": "import java.security.Permission;\nimport java.util.Collections;\n\nimport net.sourceforge.htmlunit.corejs.javascript.Context;"}, {"oldText": "    public static class ProtectedFallbackTarget {\n        public String visible() {\n            return \"visible\";\n        }\n\n        protected String protectedVisible() {\n            return \"protected\";\n        }\n    }\n\n    @Test\n", "newText": "    @Test\n"}, {"oldText": "    void fallsBackToPublicMethodsWhenDeclaredMethodAccessIsDenied() {\n        withDeclaredMemberAccessDenied(\n                () -> {\n                    Context cx = Context.enter();\n                    try {\n                        Scriptable scope = cx.initStandardObjects();\n                        NativeJavaClass wrapper =\n                                new NativeJavaClass(scope, ProtectedFallbackTarget.class, true);\n\n                        assertThat(wrapper.has(\"visible\", wrapper)).isTrue();\n                    } finally {\n                        Context.exit();\n                    }\n                });\n    }\n", "newText": "    void fallsBackToPublicMethodsWhenDeclaredMethodAccessIsDenied() {\n        Context cx = Context.enter();\n        try {\n            Scriptable scope = c